          "title": "Keep your own lid on",
          "mins": 4,
          "body": "The single biggest thing that wrecks a hard conversation is you losing your cool. The moment you raise your voice or get sarcastic, the other person stops hearing the message and starts defending themselves or firing back. Your number one job in a tough chat is to stay regulated — calm, steady, low and slow — even if they don't.\n\nThis matters most when they get heated, because they often will. If someone gets defensive or shirty, the instinct is to match it. Don't. Drop your voice, slow down, and don't take the bait. 'I can see this is frustrating — let's stay with it' beats escalating every time. You staying calm gives them permission to come back down too.\n\nA few practical tricks: pause before you respond instead of firing straight back, and don't be afraid of silence — let them sit with a point. If you feel yourself heating up, it's completely fine to say 'let's take five and come back to this'. A short break beats saying something you can't unsay. You can't control how they turn up, but you can control whether you're the calm one in the room.",
